{\trowd \lastrow \trleft0 
\clpadt30 \clpadft3 \clpadr30 \clpadfr3 \clbrdrb \clbrdrl \trql \clwWidth600 \cellx600 
\clpadt30 \clpadft3 \clpadr30 \clpadfr3 \clbrdrb \clbrdrr \trql \clwWidth4040 \cellx4640 
\intbl 
{\ri30 \li30 
{\b0 \cf31 \f2 \ri30 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li30 
{\b0 \cf31 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 
}
}
}\b0 \cf31 \f2 \ri30 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \ql \li30 \fs20 \intbl \cell \intbl 
{\ri30 \li30 
{\b0 \cf31 \f2 \ri30 \i0 \ql \fs20 \li30 
{\b0 \cf31 \f2 \ri30 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li30 
{\b0 \cf31 \f2 \ri30 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li30 
{\b0 \cf31 \f2 \ri30 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li30 
{\b0 \cf31 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa200 \sb0 
Circuit court lacked subject matter jurisdiction over declaratory judgment action brought by developer against city regarding development plans, where city\rquote s approval process for planned development under zoning code called for city review of preliminary and final site plans, developer instituted suit before city entities had opportunity to review preliminary site plan of one lot and final site plan for both lots, and developer did not allege errors so egregious or devastating that completion of site plan approval process and subsequent judicial appeal would provide remedy that was too little or too late.
\par 
}
}
